Prep the ingredients: Halve, peel, and finely dice the @yellow onion{1}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Finely dice the @celery{1}. Strip the @thyme{1/4%ounce} off the sprig and roughly chop the leaves. Slice the @mixed wild mushrooms{4%ounce}.

Heat the stock: Bring @water{3%cups} and the @veggie stock concentrate{1} to a boil in a #small pot{}.

Cook the mushrooms: Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add the mushrooms and cook, tossing, for ~{4-5%minutes}, until golden brown. Add the @peas{4%ounce}, thyme, and garlic and cook for ~{1-2%minutes} more, until fragrant. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Cook the vegetables: Heat another drizzle of oil and the @butter{1%tablespoon} in the same pan over medium heat. Add the onion and celery and cook, tossing, for ~{4-5%minutes}, until softened. Add the @Arborio rice{3/4%cup} and toss for ~{1-2%minutes}, until translucent. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Gradually add the stock: Begin adding the warm stock to the pan in 1/4 cup increments, stirring between additions, until absorbed. Continue until the rice is al dente and a loose sauce has formed, for about ~{20-30%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Finish and plate: Stir in the mushrooms, peas, and @Parmesan cheese{1%ounce} (reserving a little cheese for garnish). Serve divided between #bowls{}, sprinkled with Parmesan cheese and drizzled with olive oil. Enjoy!

> The woodsy flavors of thyme and mushrooms taste even more delicious during these chilly Winter months. Though they require a bit of attention, risottos are an easy, yet impressive weeknight dinner.